 argued that the difficulties encountered by some of the ‘new’ musicologists in their efforts to introduce a social dimension to their work are often a result of their unfamiliarity with contemporary sociological discourse.Just as linguistic studies have moved from a concern with the meaning of words to a focus on how they are used, a sociological perspective directs our attention towards the ways in which the production and reception of music inevitably involve the collaborative activities of real people in particular times and places.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusicxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aSounds and society.  aanalysis of music.  acollaborative activities.  aimprovising musicians.  amusic.  amusicologists.  asocial meanings.  asocial settings.  asocial stratification.  asociological studies.1 aMartin, Peter J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779223540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847792235423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847792235/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles